{
  format: 1
  name: text-order-is-scalar-value-not-utf16
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.1", "§A.1"]
  tags: ["ordering", "unicode"]
  note: '''
    Attack: exploit the difference between Unicode scalar-value order and
    UTF-16 code-unit order. §B.1 text is "lexicographic Unicode scalar-value
    order" — compare by codepoint. A runtime that sorts UTF-16 code units
    (a common accident in JVM/JS/UTF-16-internal stacks) misorders any string
    whose first differing character is astral, because a surrogate lead unit
    (0xD800..0xDBFF) sorts BELOW a high BMP codepoint like U+FFFD.

    Three single-character strings, codepoints spelled out:
      "z"  = U+007A            (ASCII lowercase z)
      "�"  = U+FFFD            (REPLACEMENT CHARACTER, high BMP)
      "𐀀" = U+10000           (LINEAR B SYLLABLE B008 A, first astral codepoint)

    Correct scalar order:      U+007A < U+FFFD < U+10000  ->  z, �, 𐀀
    UTF-8 byte order agrees:   7A < EF.. < F0..           ->  z, �, 𐀀
    Buggy UTF-16 unit order:   007A < D800.. < FFFD       ->  z, 𐀀, �   (WRONG)

    The corpus asserts the scalar order; the astral string must sort LAST.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.utf16@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      words: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        w: "text"
      }
      $public: {
        by_w: { $view: ".words { id, w, $sort: [w] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      words: {
        astral: { w: "𐀀" }
        repl: { w: "�" }
        ascii: { w: "z" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.by_w", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "ascii", w: "z" }
        { id: "repl", w: "�" }
        { id: "astral", w: "𐀀" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
